{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2hayden_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280604963/1949042601/0228.xml":{"full_text":"B. 0. Net Above '48\nIn March Despite\nCoal Stoppage\nBy Edward C. Stone\nNet income of the Baltimore\nOhio Railroad in March amounts\nto $1,025,378, a gain of $736,309\nover March a year ago, despite the\nfact that operations were affected\nby the coal miners' work stoppage\nwhich started on March 14. Dur\ning the month railway operating\nexpenses were cut $2,329,344.\nNet income in the first quarter\nreached $3,052,566, an increase of\n$1,427,338 over the first three\nmonths of 1948, the report stated.\nOperating revenues were not up to\nlast year, but operating expenses\nwere reduced by $3,887,643.\nABA Chief Optimistic.\nEvans Woollen, jr\u201e president of\nthe American Bankers\u2019 Association,\ntook a very optimistic view of the\nnational business outlook at the\nspring meeting of the ABA Ex\necutive Council in French Lick.\nInd. He reported a strong tone of\nconfidence among bankers, de\nclared that Inflation is over, and\ninsisted that further credit con\ntrols are not needed.\nCorcoran Thom, jr\u201e vice presi\ndent of the Riggs National Bank,\nhas returned from the annual\nmeeting of the Association of Re\nserve City Bankers held at French\nLick. Ind., just before the meeting\nof the ABA Council.\nRaymond J. Wise, of Chicago,\nformer president of Wise Brothers\nChevy Chase Dairy, has been\nelected a vice president of the\nNational Dairy Products Corp.\nKirkland Addresses Women.\nJames R. Kirkland, counsel for\nthe 8enate District Committee,\naddressed the Bank Women\u2019s Club\nof Washington, at the Burlington\nHotel, last evening, on \u2018\u2018Washing\nton and the District Committee.\u201d\nMiss Edna Oney, president of the\nclub, presided.\nS. N. Smart, of Baltimore, has\nbeen named manager of the Wash\nington branch of the Westing\nhouse Electric'Supply Co.\nPhilip L. Gore, of the Security\nStorage Co., has been appointed to\nthe Public Relations Committee of\nthe National Furniture Ware\nhousemens Association.\nPayments Total $1,610,216.\nThe New York Life Insurance\nCo. paid $1,610,216 to beneficiaries\nand living policyholders in the\nDistrict in 1948. The investment\ndepartment placed $4,544,504 in\nthe District in loans and invest\nments, bringing the total to $35,\n000,000. On January 1 the com\npany had $70,065,985 in life in\nsurance in force here.\nRobert M. Stuart, with the\nMcElfresh Agency of the Connec\nticut Mutual, is observing his 35th\nanniversary with the company to\nday* being one of the Nation\u2019s\nleading producers.\nWashington Chapter, National\nAssociation of Cbst Accountants,\nwill discuss Virginia income taxes\nover 8tatlon WEAM tomorrow at\np.m.\nBusiness Failures rose to 198 in\nthe week ended April 21 from 184\nIn the previous 'Ijtfi^Jli&d com\npared with 100 tn %lf like 1948\nweek\u2014Dun Bradstreet.\nCooper-Bessemer Corp. declared\na stock dividend of 60% on com\nmon stock, payablq-June 24. Profit\nfor three months ended March 31\nwas $271,632 or 92 cents a share\nvs. $658,441 or $2.35 a year earlier.\nAmerican Can Co. sales so far\nin 1949 are running about even\nwith record volume of a year\nearlier, officials said. Dudley W.\nFiggis was elected board chair\nman to succeed Maurice J. Sulli\nvan, who will retire. Carl H.\nBlacjr was elected president and\nWilliam C. Stolk executive vice\npresident.\nContinental Can Co. sales in the\nfirst quarter were about 4% be\nhind the same 1948 period, Chair\nman Conway told stockohlders.\nJones Laughlin Steel Corp.\nstockholders were asked by Presi\ndent and Board Chairman Ben\nMoreell to authorize an increase in\nIndebtedness and common stock.\nTexas Co. and subsidaries had\nnet income of $28,870,111 or $2.09\na share in the first 1949 quarter\nvs. $27,974,839 or $2.98 in the\nsame 1948 period.\nConsolidated Edison Co. earned\n$33,909,749 or $2.09 in 12 months\nended March 31 vs. 036.169.737 or\n$2.20 in the previous year.\nC. I. T. Financial Corp. profit for\nthe March quarter was $5,580,226\nor $1.47 vs. $3,093,360 or 86 cents\nIn the same 1948 period.\nArmco Steel Corp. net income\nfor March quarter this year was\n$8,621,791 or $2.15 vs* $5,867,347\nor $1.45 in the same 1945 period.\nColgate Palmolive Peet Co.\nearned $3,529,888 or $1.71 in\nMarch quarter vs. $3,802,884 or\n$1.85 a year earlier.\nReynolds Metals Co. profit for\nMarch quarter was $3,320,579 or\n$2.62 vs. $1,457,531 or $1.12 in the\nsame 1948 quarter.\nKoppers Co. earned $1,813,131 or\n$1.09 in March quarter vs. $1,577,\n165 or $1 27 a year earlier.\nNew England Telephone Tel\negraph Co. net income for March\nquarter was $1,454,611 or 94 cents\nvs. $1,980(219 or $1.27 in the same\n1948 period.\nBarium Steel Corp. earned $1,\n031,388 or 47 cents in March quar\nter vs. $676,062 or 34 cents a year\nearlier.\nHollingsworth Whitney Co.\nprofit for three months ended\nApril 3 was $785.3&7 or $1.66 vs.\n$910,234 or $2.24 in the same 1948\nperiod.\nElliott Co. net for March quar\nter was $762,887 or $1.99 vs. $633,\n862 or $1.73.\nBoeing Airplane Co. earned\n$577,017 or 53 cents in March\nquarter vs. a deficit of $34,615.\nClimax Molybdenum Co. net for\nquarter was $576,697 or 23\ncents'vs. $577,891 or 23 cents.\nGeneral Time Instruments Corp.\nearned $573,027 or $1.45 in 12\nweeks ended March 26 vs. $801,079\nor $2.26 a year earlier.\nAllied Mills, Inc., net for year\nended March 31 was $2,385,254 or\n$2.98 vs. $2,959,792 or $3.70 in the\npreceding fiscal period.\nVictor Chemical Works earned\n$499,751 or 58 cents in March\nquarter vs. $456,391 or 52 cents a\nyear earlier.\nN. Y. STOCK EXCHANGE j\nFaraiahed hr the Aeeacuted Freea\noaiea\u2014\n\u2022lock uc Add\nDividend Rate. 00. Blah. Low. 1:11. chae\nABBOTT LAB E X <0 >9% 39% 4 H\nAcme Steel 4 1 46% *W\nAdamt lx l.lOe 4 1S% 16% 1*% 4 V*\nAdmiral Cp 20* 11 19% 17% Id\nAffll Ola Ml 4 7% 7% 7%\nAir Reduction 1 4 11% 21% *1%-%\nAlieahanx Coro 19 7% 2% 2%\nAJIeahanv Cp of 9 43% 44%